Great choices. Let me design a clean, scalable architecture for this. I'll create a full architecture document.


Created a file, read a file
Created a file, read a file
Here's the full architecture blueprint. A few key design decisions worth calling out:

Clean 3-project solution — Web (controllers/views), Core (entities/interfaces/services), Data (EF + repos). This keeps business logic testable and decoupled from the DB layer.

Multi-tenancy via League slug — URLs like /league/the-bronx-bombers/standings make leagues feel like their own spaces. The middleware pattern means you're not passing leagueId around everywhere — it just lives in HttpContext.

Standings calculated from Games — rather than manually tracking W/L, the StandingsService recomputes from the games table whenever a score is entered. Keeps data consistent.

Player card pool is league-agnostic — players is a global table seeded with Strat-O-Matic card data. roster_slots ties players to teams per season, so cards can be reused across leagues.

Ready to start scaffolding? I'd suggest we go in this order:

Scaffold the solution — dotnet new commands, NuGet packages, EF setup
Migrations — stand up the DB schema
Identity + Auth — login/register
