Architected Lahman database integration for player and statistics data
Architected Lahman database integration for player and statistics data
Smart call. The Lahman database covers complete MLB batting, pitching, and fielding stats back to 1871 
Society for American Baseball Research
 — perfect for a Strat-O-Matic platform where cards are tied to specific player seasons. Let me update the architecture to fully integrate it.


Created 2 files, ran a command, read a file
Created 2 files, ran a command, read a file
Architecture updated. Here's what changed and why it matters:

Two-schema database — public for app data, lahman for the imported baseball data. This is the key structural decision. It means you can re-download and reimport a new Lahman release every January without any risk to your league/roster/standings data.

player_cards table replaces the old players table — a card is now just (lahman_player_id, card_year), a soft reference into the Lahman schema. This is exactly how Strat-O-Matic works — a 1986 Mike Schmidt card is a distinct thing from a 1980 Mike Schmidt card, and both pull their stats from Lahman.

New DataImport CLI project — a standalone dotnet run tool that reads the Lahman CSVs and populates the lahman schema. Kept separate from the main app so it can be run independently and safely re-run annually.

Lahman entities are read-only in EF Core — mapped with .ToTable("people", "lahman") but excluded from migrations. The app never writes to them.

Stats computed on the fly — BA, OBP, SLG, ERA, WHIP are derived in PlayerCardService from raw Lahman counting stats, never stored. Cleaner and more flexible.

Ready to start scaffolding the solution? I can generate the dotnet new commands, initial project files, and the EF Core setup for both schemas.

