12:42 PM

Architected multi-layered stats model separating historical and simulated data
Architected multi-layered stats model separating historical and simulated data
Good catch — this is an important data model distinction. Every player card has two stat contexts:

Historical stats (Lahman, read-only) — what the real player actually did
Simulated stats (per league season) — what the card accumulates in that specific league's games
The same 1986 Mike Schmidt card could be in 10 different leagues and have 10 different sim stat lines. Let me update the architecture to reflect this cleanly.


Ran a command, created a file, read a file
Ran a command, created a file, read a file
Architecture updated. The key changes:

sim_batting_stats / sim_pitching_stats tables — scoped to (card_id, season_id). The same 1986 Schmidt card can have 10 independent stat lines across 10 leagues. A UNIQUE constraint on that pair enforces one sim line per card per season.

player_cards is shared, sim stats are not — the card definition (lahman_player_id + card_year) is a global table reused across leagues. Only the simulated stats are tenant-scoped. This avoids duplicating card definitions while keeping stat lines fully isolated.

roster_slots has a UNIQUE (season_id, card_id) — a card can only be on one team per league season, which is how Strat leagues work. Cross-league uniqueness is intentionally not enforced (the same card can be in multiple leagues simultaneously).

PlayerCardService assembles both contexts — it returns a PlayerCardStats object with both the historical Lahman line and the sim line (which is null if that card isn't in the current league). The player profile page renders them side-by-side.

One thing worth flagging for V2: once you add box score entry, you'll want a game_batting_lines / game_pitching_lines table to record per-player per-game results, and SimStatsService will aggregate those into the sim stat totals. V1 can skip that and just track team-level wins/losses.

